7            Establishing and Maintaining the Environment

This section describes how an organization establishes and maintains EPPORAs environment. It discusses how users and projects are created, attributes including project requirements and schedule tasks are specified, new labor categories created, how to specify the use of calendars and how project ranking criteria are specified. It also describes how divisions are specified and how general options and triggers are modified. The establishing/maintaining of the EPPORA environment is accomplished by Administrators, Business Analysts, Project Managers and Project Portfolio Managers and by all users for some of their own user attributes.

7.1 Users

An Administrator establishes a users initial attributes by creating a new user. Another method is to import new user attributes from existing popular software tools that already contains user attributes such as Oracle, DB2, Microsoft SQL, SAP, etc. The users attributes are maintained by Project Portfolio Managers and the users themselves. An Executive establishes and updates the users salary. An Administrator opens the Users page shown in Figures 11 by selecting the Administration tabs Users command. Each user must be at least one User Type and can be multiple user types. Depending on the user type of the individual that invoked the User command, different objects within the page are enabled. The User Search page shown in Figure 9 is used to select an existing user or to create a new user (Insert New User button). Since EPPORA can support millions of users, the User Search page uses four filters for determining the selected users. If no filter is specified, then all users are available for selection. Any combination of the four filters can be used, which are:

 

  1. The user type (s)
  2. The users first, last, partial or full name
  3. The labor categories
  4. The divisions

Figure 9User Search Page

 

The results of a User Search are shown in Figure 10. The resulting user list is displayed in groups of twenty-five (default which can be changed using the Options command from the Administration tab). After selecting the desired user (note if multiple users are selected, only the initial user is used) the EPPORA Users page is displayed as shown in Figure 11.

7.2 Projects

Project Portfolio Managers establish new projects by selecting the Project tabs Projects command. This action opens the Project List page shown in Figure 13. A projects information can only be created and updated by the assigned Project Manager, Business Analyst and the Project Portfolio Manager. EPPORA uses two special icons for editing (!) and deleting (X). Only a Project Portfolio Manager can delete a project. A Business Analyst along with a Project Portfolio Manager can create and modify a projects requirements.

A Project Manager, a Business Analyst and a Project Portfolio Manager can map a projects requirements to the relevant project schedule tasks. A Project Manager along with a Project Portfolio Manager can create and modify a projects schedule tasks. Note that a single individual can be any combination of Business Analyst, Project Manager and/or Project Portfolio Manager for a project. Only a Project Portfolio Manager can change a projects other attributes.

Figure 13Project List Page

When a Business Analyst, Project Manager or Project Portfolio Manager selects a project (!) or selects the Insert New button on the Projects List page, then the Project Attributes page is displayed (see Figure 14).

Figure 14Project Attributes Page

By selecting one of the people icons a Project Portfolio Manager establishes for this project the Business Analyst, Project Manager, Project Portfolio Manager and the projects Sponsor. The projects name for a new project is specified along with which division the project will be based from during its implementation. If critical path tasks are to be ranked higher than non-critical path tasks for this project, than a value can be specified using the Critical Path Factor drop-down list. When the Project List page is active, selecting the Edit button (pencil icon) causes the Project Attributes page to be displayed. Selecting the Delete button (X) by a Project Portfolio Manager causes the project to be deleted.

When a Business Analyst, Project Manager or a Project Portfolio Manager selects the Analyze Project button from the Project Attributes page, the EPPORA Project Analyzer critiques the designated project and displays the results of its analysis as shown in Figure 15.

 

Figure 15Project Analyzer Page

 

EPPORA supports multiple baselines for each project. Each baseline contains all the relevant requirements, schedule, mapping and test information for the designated project. A project can have four different statuses, which are:

  1. Interim used by Business Analyst and Project Manager to save current status of project. If in going back in the history there was a previous Approve baseline prior to a Suspended baseline, then resources will be allocated to the interim baseline. If there was a Suspended baseline prior to an Approve baseline, then there will be no allocation for the designated project.
  2. Approve indicates that a Project Portfolio Manager has approved this baseline. This is used usually for major baselines at the completion of a key deliverable or milestone.
  3. Suspended used to signify the project will not have any resources allocated.
  4. Completed designates the project is completed and there will be no more resources allocated to this project.

When a Business Analyst, Project Manager or a Project Portfolio Manager selects the Requirements button from the Project Attributes page, the Project Requirements page is displayed as shown in Figure 17. A Project Manager, Business Analyst and/or Project Portfolio Manager establishes/updates the mapping and/or testing of requirements to schedule tasks. A Business Analyst or a Project Portfolio Manager can establish/update the requirements. A Project Manager can display the requirements. As discussed in Section 4.5, EPPORA uses a Structured Tabular method for creating, maintaining and displaying the requirements. The Structured Tabular method lends itself to creating requirements that are unambiguous and that are readily testable. The Title column information is indented one space for each level, making the understanding of a projects requirements hierarchy readily visible and easier to understand.

 

When a Business Analyst or a Project Portfolio Manager demotes a requirement, he/she is decreasing the requirements level by one and if the requirement is a parent requirement, then he/she is demoting all its children and childrens children (ad infinitum) one level as well. When a Business Analyst or Project Portfolio Manager promotes a requirement, he/she is increasing the level of the requirement. You can only promote a requirement if the preceding requirements level is greater than or equal to the requirement being promoted. EPPORA uses a Requirements Dynamic Action List for performing specific actions relative to each requirement. These actions include inserting a new requirement, deleting an existing requirement and optionally its children requirements, promoting the level of a requirement making it a child of the preceding requirement, demoting the level of a requirement and editing a requirement.

It also includes creating/updating a mapping between the projects requirements and its schedule tasks and linking the requirements to the appropriate test cases for each low-level requirement. The Requirements Dynamic Action List is accessed by moving the mouse pointer to the designated requirement and selecting it (clicking anywhere on the requirements row). EPPORA highlights the selected requirement row and displays the Requirements Dynamic Action List as shown in Figure 17.

Figure 17Project Requirements Page

When the Customized command is selected, EPPORA displays a drop-down list of requirement levels starting at 0 and going for as many levels as there are in the specified projects requirements. The Customized Drop-Down List allows users to look at a projects high-level requirements without delving into the detailed requirements and quickly ascertain the major functionality being provided by the project. It also allows the user to format the Requirements Display shown in Figure 17. A Business Analyst or Project Portfolio Manager can select which fields shall be displayed, the order (as shown in Figure 18) for the Requirements Display and which levels shall be displayed (default is all) as shown in Figure 19.

Figure 21Schedule Tasks Page

The Project Manager or Project Portfolio Manager when creating or maintaining a project schedule should make use of task dependencies. It is through task dependencies that a critical path is determined and provides the tools needed to assure proper emphasis is placed on the critical path tasks. Critical path tasks help to assure that the schedule is delivered on time. Figure 21 shows an example Schedule Tasks page. The Schedule Task page is invoked from the Project Attributes page. The Project Manager and/or Project Portfolio Manager can set additional task attributes. When a new schedule is created, there are no tasks displayed in the Schedule Tasks page. The Schedule Task Dynamic Action List is accessed by moving the mouse pointer to the designated schedule task and selecting it (clicking anywhere on the schedule task row). EPPORA highlights the selected schedule task row and displays the Schedule Task Dynamic Action List just like it does for the requirements display.

Prior to the EPPORA automatic allocation period, the Project Portfolio Managers can specify what resources must be used for their projects. EPPORA then uses this information in its algorithm when assigning actual labor resources for each generic labor resource for the tasks. This assures that the actual resource is not re-assigned by EPPORA. The Permanent Assignment Page is used by a Project Manage or Project Portfolio Manager to override EPPORAs automatic assignment of labor resources to a generic resource.

Figure 28Labor Resource Assignment Page

7.5 Triggers

An integral part of EPPORA is its ability to diagnose potentially dangerous conditions that affect a projects budget, scope or schedule. Each of the triggers, when they occur, causes EPPORA to send an internal message and optionally an e-mail to a designated set of users. Triggers usually automatically send a message to the relevant Project Manager, Business Analyst, Project Portfolio Manager and Sponsor for events concerning projects. A few triggers send messages to Administrators and Executives. In addition, the Administrator or the Project Portfolio Manager can specify a set of users that the triggers message should be sent to when it occurs and if in addition to the internal EPPORA message an e-mail shall also be sent. Figure 34 is the Triggers Page used to establish the Trigger options. The Triggers Page is invoked from the Administration menu using the Triggers command.

7.8 Criteria

The Criteria Page is used to adjust the importance of each criterion and/or to add additional criteria for determining the ranking of projects. The Criteria Page is invoked from the Home Page Administration tab. The Criteria Page is used by Project Portfolio Managers to determine which projects should be implemented and which projects shall receive the most productive resources within the organization. Only a Project Portfolio Manager can update or delete a criterion by selecting Criteria command from the Administration tab. This action causes Figure 39 to be displayed.

 

Figure 39Criteria List Page

 

If the Project Portfolio Manager clicks on the update indicator (!) then Figure 40 is displayed, where the Criteria Name, Weight (Importance) and Responsibilities are specified.

 

Figure 40Update Criteria Page

 

 

You cannot delete a default criterion. If you set the weight (Importance) to zero, you are removing the criterions use in the ranking of the projects. If you insert a new criterion you can delete the non-default criterion by selecting the (X) specified in the Action column of the Criteria List display for the designated criterion row, as shown in Figure 41.

 

Figure 41Delete Criteria Page

The Criteria Response Page is used to score a specific criterion. Only an assigned Responder for a project can provide a score for a designated criterion. As the evaluation of a specific criterion for a project changes, such as Cost, a responder can update the projects score for that criterion, thus keeping the ranking of projects in the portfolio up to date. To determine the ranking of a project, EPPORA multiplies each projects score for each criterion, times the criterion weight (importance) and then sums all the criterions scores for the designated project to determine the projects ranking. The Criterion Response page is invoked by selecting the Project tabs Criterion Scoring command. This causes the display of Figure 42.
